.SH Store::Indexed(3)
.SS NAME
.PP
\f[B]Store::Indexed\f[R] - A fast, key-indexed data store with dual XS
and Pure-Perl backends.
.SS SYNOPSIS
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
use Store::Indexed;

# Auto-detects best backend (XS preferred)
my $store = Store::Indexed->new();

# Or force a specific backend
use Store::Indexed \[aq]:xs\[aq];
my $store = Store::Indexed->new(backend => \[aq]XS\[aq]);

$store->set(1, \[dq]my_key\[dq], \[dq]data\[dq]);
my $val = $store->get(1, \[dq]my_key\[dq]);
\f[R]
.fi
.SS DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]Store::Indexed\f[R] provides an interface for storing and
retrieving data points indexed by an integer ID and a string name.
It supports both a highly optimized C-based implementation
(\f[V]XS\f[R]) and a portable \f[V]Pure-Perl\f[R] implementation
(\f[V]PP\f[R]).
.SS IMPORT TAGS
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]:xs\f[R] - Forces the use of the \f[V]Store::Indexed::XS\f[R]
backend.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]:pp\f[R] - Forces the use of the \f[V]Store::Indexed::PP\f[R]
backend.
.SS METHODS
.SS new(%args)
.PP
Creates a new \f[V]Store::Indexed\f[R] instance.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]backend\f[R]: Can be set to \f[V]\[aq]XS\[aq]\f[R] or
\f[V]\[aq]PP\[aq]\f[R] to override environment or import settings.
.SS set($id, $name, $value)
.PP
Associates a scalar \f[V]$value\f[R] with a composite key of
\f[V]$id\f[R] and \f[V]$name\f[R].
.SS get($id, $name)
.PP
Returns the scalar value associated with the specified \f[V]$id\f[R] and
\f[V]$name\f[R], or \f[V]undef\f[R] if not found.
.PP
   *   *   *   *   *
.SH Store::Indexed::XS(3)
.SS DESCRIPTION
.PP
The \f[V]XS\f[R] backend provides a memory-efficient implementation
utilizing \f[V]uthash\f[R] for O(1) average-time complexity lookups.
This module is intended for production environments where performance is
critical.
.SS REQUIREMENTS
.IP \[bu] 2
A C compiler (e.g., \f[V]gcc\f[R], \f[V]clang\f[R])
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]khashl.h\f[R] library (included in source)
.IP \[bu] 2
Perl 5.10+
.PP
   *   *   *   *   *
.SH Store::Indexed::PP(3)
.SS DESCRIPTION
.PP
The \f[V]PP\f[R] (Pure-Perl) backend provides a fallback implementation
for environments where compiling C extensions is not possible (e.g.,
restricted hosting, cross-compilation targets).
.SS NOTES
.PP
While functionally equivalent to the \f[V]XS\f[R] backend, the
\f[V]PP\f[R] version maintains data in a standard Perl hash, which may
consume more memory for large datasets compared to the \f[V]XS\f[R]
implementation.
.PP
   *   *   *   *   *
.SS ENVIRONMENT
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]STORE_BACKEND\f[R]: Set to \f[V]XS\f[R] or \f[V]PP\f[R] to globally
define the preferred backend for the current process.
.SS SEE ALSO
.PP
\f[V]XSLoader\f[R], \f[V]perlxs\f[R], \f[V]perlobject\f[R]
